FEC Rules on Democratic Rep. Eric Swalwell’s Use of Campaign Funds By Caden Pearson July 27, 2022 Updated: July 27, 2022

The Federal Election Commission (FEC) on Tuesday announced that it has denied a request by Rep. Eric Swalwell (D-Ca.) to use campaign funds to pay for childcare expenses when he travels to support other Democratic campaigns and at the request of foreign governments and entities.
...
The Democratic congressman also courted controversy over his past ties to an alleged Chinese Communist Party spy, known as Fang Fang or Christine Fang.
A report by Axios in December 2020 claimed that Fang built up an extensive network of contacts with up-and-coming politicians in the San Francisco Bay Area, including Swalwell. The report said Swalwell cut ties with the alleged spy after investigators gave him a “defensive briefing.”

Republicans sought to remove Swalwell from his position in the House Select Committee on Intelligence in May 2021, but Democrats in the House voted the resolution down.

Biden Administration Officials Subpoenaed Over Big Tech Censorship Collusion

The suspected collusion between Big Tech and Big Government is nothing new, but now the issue is playing out in court: in May, a lawsuit filed at the US District Court for the Western District Court of Louisiana seeks to prove that such inappropriate ties in fact exist.

The plaintiffs are the states of Missouri and Louisiana while President Biden and senior figures from his White House— including Dr. Fauci—are named as defendants. The allegation is that the collusion to suppress speech happened specifically around topics like COVID-19 and election security, and that this was done with the pretense of fighting “misinformation.”

Fauci and others must reveal if they have communicated or held meetings with Big Tech regarding “misinformation moderation” and present these communications. Facebook and others must do the same, regarding meetings and communications with administration officials.

The discovery request for Dr. Fauci and the NIAID can be found here and here.

The discovery request for Jen Easterly and the CISA can be found here and here.

The discovery request for the CDC can be found here.

The discovery request for DHS can be found here.

The discovery request for HHS can be found here.

The discovery request for White House Press Secretary Karine Jean-Pierre can be found here.

The discovery request for Nina Jankowicz can be found here.

The discovery request for Surgeon General Vivek Murthy can be found here.

The subpoena sent to Meta can be found here.

The subpoena sent to Youtube can be found here.

The subpoena to Twitter can be found here.

The subpoena sent to Instagram can be found here.

The subpoena sent to LinkedIn can be found here.

They all have a month to respond. “We will fight to get to the bottom of this alleged collusion and expose the suppression of freedom of speech by social media giants at the behest of top-ranking government officials,” said Missouri Attorney General Eric Schmitt.

Source: Reclaim the Net
